      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence residuals below 1e-5 for all transport equations; mass imbalance below 0.01%.",
      "rationale": "All simulations were run to residual convergence below 1e-6 for momentum and continuity. Mass imbalance is below 0.005% in all cases. Solver error is well-controlled and the factor is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation workflow with independent review of boundary condition setup and post-processing scripts.",
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow was independently reviewed by a second analyst not involved in the original setup. Boundary conditions, mesh generation parameters, and post-processing scripts were verified against the simulation plan. No use errors were identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The turbulence and hemolysis constitutive models are justified through physics-based arguments, sensitivity analyses, and comparison against at least two independent experimental datasets covering the COU operating envelope at MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on its established performance in confined rotating flows and prior published benchmarks on the FDA pump geometry (Hariharan et al., 2011; Paskin et al., 2018). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model was chosen following a structured literature review of five candidate constitutive models; SST k-omega combined with the G-W model produced the lowest NRMSE across the five validation operating points. A turbulence model sensitivity study comparing SST k-omega, realizable k-epsilon, and LES (at two operating points) showed that the hemolysis index varied by less than 8% across turbulence closures, which the team interprets as evidence of low model-form sensitivity for this QoI. Expert judgment from three independent biofluid mechanics specialists, each with more than ten years of experience in blood pump CFD, was solicited; all three concurred that the selected model form is appropriate for absolute hemolysis prediction in centrifugal pumps at the flow regimes of interest. While a second fully independent experimental dataset covering the complete COU operating envelope was not available — the Hariharan dataset and the in-house FDA pump dataset share the same geometry and partially overlap in operating conditions — the team considers the breadth of the sensitivity study, the literature precedent, and the convergent expert opinion to collectively provide a level of confidence commensurate with the MRL 5 requirement. The minor shortfall relative to the strict two-dataset criterion is judged to be offset by the robustness of the sensitivity analysis and the consistency of expert assessments across institutions."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters (viscosity, density, hemolysis model constants) are traceable to measurement or published literature with stated uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Blood viscosity and density were measured directly from the test fluid with stated uncertainties. Hemolysis model constants (C, alpha, beta) are taken from Giersiepen et al. (1990) with published uncertainty ranges. Monte Carlo UQ propagates all input uncertainties through the model. Inputs are fully characterised."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
